tyle=\"text-align:left;\"\n| colspan=\"5\" | ''Did not bat'': [[Laura Marsh]], [[Katherine Brunt]], [[Isa Guha]]\n|}\n{| style=\"text-align: center; width: 60%;\" class=wikitable\n|+ [[New Zealand women's national cricket team|New Zealand]] bowling\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowler]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Overs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Maidens]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Run (cricket)|Runs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Wicket]]s\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Economy rate (cricket)|Economy]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sophie Devine]] \n| 9 || 0 || 30 || 0 || 3.33\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Kate Pulford]] \n| 3 || 0 || 17 || 0 || 5.66\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Nicola Browne]] \n| 7 || 1 || 24 || 0 || 3.42\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Suzie Bates]] \n| 4.1 || 0 || 21 || 0 || 5.04\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Lucy Doolan]] \n| 10 || 4 || 23 || 3 || 2.30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sarah Tsukigawa]] \n| 4 || 1 || 23 || 0 || 5.75\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Aimee Watkins|Aimee Mason]] \n| 9 || 0 || 28 || 2 || 3.11\n|}\n\n'''Match officials'''\n* On-field [[umpire (cricket)|umpires]]: [[Steve Davis (umpire)|Steve Davis]] and [[Brian Jerling]]\n* [[Third umpire]]: [[Tyron Wijewardene]]\n* [[Match referee]]: [[Brian Aldridge (cricketer)|Brian Aldridge]]\n* [[Fourth umpire|Reserve umpire]]: [[Jeff Brookes]]\n\n'''Key'''\n* {{asterisk}} \u2013 [[Captain (cricket)|Captain]]\n* {{dagger}} \u2013 [[Wicket-keeper]]\n* c ''Fielder'' \u2013 Indicates that the batter was dismissed by a catch by the named [[Fielding (cricket)|fielder]]\n* b ''Bowler'' \u2013 Indicates which [[Bowling (cricket)|bowler]] gains credit for the dismissal\n* lbw \u2013 Indicates the batter was dismissed [[leg before wicket]]\n* st \u2013 Indicates the batter was [[stumped]]\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe ICC awarded England US$45,000 for their cup win, while New Zealand received $25,000.<ref name=\"tears\"/> Shaw, who had not expected to play, said after the match; \"I started the day crying, I finished it crying, but we won a World Cup in between\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/23/women-england-cricket-world-cup |title=England win the World Cup |last=Booth |first=Lawrence |author-link=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |work=The Guardian |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> New Zealand's captain, Tiffen, reflected after the match, \"Maybe there were some nerves in amongst the camp. We didn't hype it up to be anything more than another day at the office, unfortunately it was a bad day at the office.\"<ref name=\"tears\"/> The team of the tournament included seven finalists: England's Edwards was selected as captain, and was joined by teammates Brunt, Marsh, Claire Taylor and Sarah Taylor. Bates and Pulford represented New Zealand in the team, while Devine was named as the team's twelfth woman. Claire Taylor, who finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer, was named as the player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/396488.html |title=Five England players in World Cup XI |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> The month after the final, Taylor became the first woman to be selected as one of [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year|''Wisden's'' Cricketers of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/5096209/Claire-Taylor-the-first-woman-to-be-named-among-the-Wisden-Cricketers-of-the-Year.html |title=Claire Taylor the first woman to be named among the Wisden Cricketers of the Year |last=Berry |first=Scyld |authorlink=Scyld Berry |work=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |location=London |date=3 April 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe England team flew back to the United Kingdom in [[economy class]]; Mitchell highlighted the contrast with the [[England cricket team|England men's team]], who \"fly business as standard\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2009/03/world_champions.shtml |title=World champions return home |last=Mitchell |first=Alison |author-link=Alison Mitchell |work=BBC Sport |date=24 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> They held a reception at Lord's in London upon their return, but the former [[Minister for Sport and Civil Society|sports minister]], [[Richard Caborn]], lamented the low-key celebrations, saying that \"I would have a Number 10 reception, a reception at the House of Commons, and, at the appropriate time, in the Lords.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/25/england-womens-world-cup-winners |title=England women's cricket team bring back the cup \u2013 and the pride |last=Gibson |first=Owen |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe two sides met again three months later to contest the final of the [[2009 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2009 Women's World Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/engine/match/355990.html |title=Final: England Women v New Zealand Women at Lord's, Jun 21, 2009 |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 April 2012}}</ref> England once again won the contest, and in doing so became the first team of either gender to be champions in all three cricketing formats: [[Women's Test cricket|Test]], [[Women's One Day International|One Day International]] and [[Women's Twenty20 International|Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/content/story/409994.html |title=All-conquering England take title |last=Narayanan |first=Nishi |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> Each of the top four in the 2009 tournament automatically qualified for the [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/kiwi-bates-does-a-sehwag-world-cup/20090319.htm |title=Kiwi Bates does a Sehwag in World Cup |work=[[Rediff.com]] |date=19 March 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Neither England nor New Zealand reached the final of that tournament, but instead met in the third-place playoff, which England won by four wickets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.ndtv.com/icc-womens-world-cup/news/203626-charlotte-edwards-guides-england-to-third-spot-in-womens-world-cup |title=Charlotte Edwards guides England to third spot in Women's World Cup |agency=Press Trust of India |publisher=[[NDTV]] |date=15 February 2013 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{2009 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England women's cricket team}}\n{{New Zealand women's national cricket team}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:2008\u201309 Australian women's cricket season|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in English women's cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand women's sport|cricket]]\n[[Category:2009 Women's Cricket World Cup|!]]\n[[Category:England women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:Women's Cricket World Cup finals]]\n", "name_user": "Harrias", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:rem dup link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_Women%27s_Cricket_World_Cup_Final"}
{"title_page": "Mulug, Siddipet district", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Mulug\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = \n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = <!--India Telangana-->\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Telangana, India\n| coordinates             = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Telangana]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Siddipet]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 502279\n| registration_plate      = TS 36\n| blank1_name_sec1        = Nearest city\n| blank1_info_sec1        = [[HYDERABAD]]\n| website                 = {{URL|telangana.gov.in}} \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Mulug''' is a [[Tehsil|Mandal]] in [[Siddipet district]] of [[Telangana State]], India.<ref>{{cite web |title=District Level Mandal wise list of villages in Siddipet district|url=http://apland.ap.nic.in/cclaweb/Districts_Alphabetical/medak.pdf |website=Chief Commissioner of Land Administration|publisher=National Informatics Centre|accessdate=5 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094713/http://apland.ap.nic.in/cclaweb/Districts_Alphabetical/medak.pdf|archivedate=2 April 2015|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nThe villages in Mulug mandal includes:Narsampally, Achaipalle, Aliabad, Annasagar, Bahilampur, Banda Mailaram, Baswapuram, Chinnathimapur, Damarakunta, Dasarlapalle, Gangadharapalle, Karkapatla, Kasireddypally, Ksheerasagar, Vagunoothi, Vantimamidi, Kamalabad, Kokkonda, Kolthur, Kotiyal, Lakshmakkapalle, Mamidiyal, Markook, Mulug, Nagireddypalle, Narsapur, Singannagudem, Surampur, Tunkibollaram, Zapthisingaipalle etc..\n\nRecently,Telangana High Court halts the Eviction of Mulugu Villagers.The Telangana high court has ordered instructing the government not to release water resulting in inundation of their localities under Kondapochamma Reservoir which has relieved many villagers of Bahilampur and Mamidyala in Siddipet district.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://libertatem.in/law/high-court/telangana-high-court-halts-eviction-of-mulugu-villagers/|title=Telangana High Court halts Eviction of Mulugu Villagers \u00bb Libertatem.in|date=2020-04-15|website=Libertatem.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Telangana}}\n\n[[Category:Mandal headquarters in Siddipet district]]\n[[Category:Villages in Siddipet district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Mulug\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| ni