ategory:Critics of religions]]\n[[Category:Cultural critics]]\n[[Category:Epistemologists]]\n[[Category:Ethicists]]\n[[Category:Executed ancient Greek people]]\n[[Category:Executed philosophers]]\n[[Category:Family of Socrates]]\n[[Category:Forced suicides]]\n[[Category:Founders of philosophical traditions]]\n[[Category:History of education]]\n[[Category:History of ideas]]\n[[Category:History of logic]]\n[[Category:History of philosophy]]\n[[Category:Irony theorists]]\n[[Category:Logicians]]\n[[Category:Meta-ethics]]\n[[Category:Metaphilosophers]]\n[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\n[[Category:Moral philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ontologists]]\n[[Category:People executed by ancient Athens]]\n[[Category:People executed by poison]]\n[[Category:People executed for heresy]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of art]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of culture]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of education]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of ethics and morality]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of law]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of literature]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of logic]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of love]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of mind]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of science]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of social science]]\n[[Category:Philosophy writers]]\n[[Category:Political philosophers]]\n[[Category:Rationality theorists]]\n[[Category:Religious skeptics]]\n[[Category:Social commentators]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:Social philosophers]]\n[[Category:Theorists on Western civilization]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n[[Category:Western philosophy]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek philosophers]]\n", "name_user": "Uscbino", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArrest of Leon:trying to make more comprehensible the episode reported also in Plato's Apology etc", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Socrates"}
{"title_page": "Sri Lankan junglefowl", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Sri Lankan junglefowl\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{Cite iucn | author = BirdLife International | title = ''Gallus lafayettii'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22679209A92807515 | date = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22679209A92807515.en }}</ref>\n| image = Flickr - Rainbirder - Ceylon Junglefowl (Gallus lafayetii) Male.jpg\n| image_caption = Male in [[Sinharaja Forest Reserve]], Sri Lanka\n| genus = Gallus\n| species = lafayettii\n| authority = [[Ren\u00e9-Primev\u00e8re Lesson|Lesson]], 1831\n| range_map = Gallus lfeyetii map.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Range\n}}\n\nThe '''Sri Lankan junglefowl''' (''Gallus lafayettii''), also known as the '''Ceylon junglefowl''', is a member of the  [[Galliformes]] bird order which is [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] to [[Sri Lanka]], where it is the [[national bird]]. It is closely related to the [[red junglefowl]] (''G. gallus''), the wild [[junglefowl]] from which the chicken was domesticated. However, a whole-genome molecular study rather show that Sri Lankan junglefowl and [[grey junglefowl]] are genetically sister species than with the red junglefowl.<ref name=Lawal>{{ cite journal | last1=Lawal | first1=RA. | display-authors=etal  | year=2020 | title=The wild species genome ancestry of domestic chickens | journal=BMC Biology | volume=18 | issue=13 | pages=13 | doi=10.1186/s12915-020-0738-1 | doi-access=free | pmid=32050971 }}</ref> Sri Lankan junglefowl and red junglefowl diverged about 2.8 million years ago whereas, time of divergence between the Sri Lankan junglefowl and grey junglefowl was 1.8 million years ago.<ref name = Lawal /> \n\nEvidence of introgressive hybridization from Sri Lanka junglefowl has also been established in domestic chicken.<ref name = Lawal /> The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] of the Sri Lankan junglefowl commemorates the French aristocrat [[Gilbert du Motier, marquis de La Fayette]]. In [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]], it is known as {{lang|si|\u0dc0\u0dc5\u0dd2 \u0d9a\u0dd4\u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dc5\u0dcf}} ({{transl|si|wali kukula}})<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnhsenvis.nic.in/pdf/vol%203%20(1).pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-10-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401015111/http://www.bnhsenvis.nic.in/pdf/vol%203%20%281%29.pdf |archive-date=2010-04-01 |df= }}</ref> and in [[Tamil language|Tamil]], it is known as \u0b87\u0bb2\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bcb\u0bb4\u0bbf (''ila\u1e45kaik k\u0101\u1e6d\u1e6dukk\u014d\u1e3bi'').\n{{Cladogram\n|caption=[[Cladogram]] showing the species in the genus ''[[Gallus (genus)|Gallus]]''.<ref name = Lawal /><ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Tiley | first1=G.P. | last2=Pandey | first2=A. | last3=Kimball | first3=R.T. | last4=Braun | first4=E.L. | last5=Burleigh | first5=J.G. | year=2020| title=Whole genome phylogeny of ''Gallus'': introgression and data\u2011type effects | journal=Avian Research | volume=11 | issue=7 | doi=10.1186/s40657-020-00194-w | doi-access=free }}</ref>\n|align=right\n|cladogram={{Cladex| style=font-size:80%;line-height:75%;width:320px;\n|label1=''Gallus''&nbsp; \n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=[[Grey junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus sonneratii''\n         |2=[[Sri Lankan junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus lafayettii''\n         }}\n      |2=[[Red junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus gallus''\n      }}\n    |2=[[Green junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus varius''\n    }}\n}}\n}}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Flickr - Rainbirder - Ceylon Junglefowl (Gallus lafayetii) female.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Female at [[Sinharaja Forest Reserve]], Sri Lanka]]\nAs with other junglefowl, the Sri Lankan junglefowl is strongly [[sexually dimorphic]]; the male is much larger than the female, with more vivid plumage and a highly exaggerated wattle and comb.\n\nThe male Sri Lankan junglefowl ranges from {{convert|66|\u2013|72|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length<ref>del Hoyo, J. Elliott, A. and Sargatal, J. [[Handbook of the Birds of the World]] [[Lynx Edicions]], [[Barcelona]]</ref> and {{convert|790|-|1140|g|lb|abbr=on}} in weight, essentially resembling a large, muscular [[rooster]].<ref name = \"CRC\">''CRC Handbook of Avian Body Masses'' by John B. Dunning Jr. (Editor). CRC Press (1992), {{ISBN|978-0-8493-4258-5}}.</ref> The male has orange-red body plumage, and dark purple to black wings and tail. The feathers of the mane descending from head to base of [[Vertebral column|spine]] are golden, and the face has bare red skin and wattles. The comb is red with a yellow centre.  As with the [[green junglefowl]], the cock does not possess an [[Plumage#Eclipse plumage|eclipse plumage]].\n\nThe female is much smaller, at only {{convert|35|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|510|-|645|g|lb|abbr=on}} in weight, with dull brown [[plumage]] with white patterning on the lower belly and breast, ideal [[camouflage]] for a nesting bird.<ref name= \"CRC\"/>\n\n==Classification==\nThis is one of four [[species]] of birds in the genus ''[[Gallus (biology)|Gallus]]''. The other three members of the genus are [[red junglefowl]] (''G. gallus''), [[grey junglefowl]] (''G. sonneratii''), and [[green junglefowl]] (''G. varius'').\n\nThe Sri Lankan junglefowl is most closely related to the grey junglefowl,<ref>International Chicken Polymorphism Map Consortium {{cite journal | last1 = Wong | first1 = GK| year = 2004 | title = A genetic variation map for chicken with 2.8 million single-nucleotide polymorphisms | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 432 | issue = | pages = 717\u2013722 | doi = 10.1038/nature03156 | pmid = 15592405 | pmc=2263125|display-authors=etal}}</ref> though physically the male resembles the red junglefowl. Female Sri Lanka junglefowl are very similar to those of the grey junglefowl. Like the green junglefowl, Sri Lankan junglefowl are island species that have evolved side by side with their similarly stranded island predators and competitors. Uniquely complex anti-predator behaviors and foraging strategies are integral components in the long evolutionary story of the Sri Lankan junglefowl.\n\n==Behaviour==\nAs with other jungle fowl, Sri Lankan jungle fowl are primarily terrestrial. They spend most of their time foraging for food by scratching the ground for various [[seed]]s, fallen [[fruit]], and [[insect]]s.\n\nFemales lay two to four [[Egg (biology)|egg]]s in a nest, either on the forest floor in steep hill country or in the abandoned nests of other birds and squirrels. Like the grey and green junglefowl, male Sri Lankan junglefowl play an active role in nest protection and chick rearing.\n\n==Reproduction==\n[[File:Gallus lafayettii MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.9.31.jpg|thumb| ''Gallus lafayettii'' - [[MHNT]]]]\n[[File:Gallus lafayetii.jpg|thumb]]\nThe reproductive strategy of this species is best described as facultative [[polyandry]], in that a single female is typically linked with two or three males that form a pride of sorts. These males are likely to be siblings. The female pairs with the alpha male of the pride and nests high off the ground.\n\nHer eggs are highly variable in colour, but generally are cream with a yellow or pink tint. Purple or brownish spots are common.\n\nOccasionally, a female produces red eggs or blotched eggs.\n\nThe hen incubates her eggs, while the alpha male guards her nest from a nearby perch during the nesting season. The beta males remain in close proximity, and guard the nesting territory from intruders or potential predators, such as rival males, or snakes and mongooses. Sri Lankan junglefowl are unique amongst the junglefowl in the brevity of their incubation, which may be as short as 20 days as contrasted with the 21\u201326 days of the green junglefowl.\n\nThe chicks require a constant diet of live food, usually insects and isopods such as [[sowbug]]s and [[pillbug]]s. In particular, the juveniles of [[land crab]]s are also highly important to the growth and survivability of the juvenile and subadult Sri Lankan junglefowl. In captivity, this species is particularly vulnerable to a poultry disease caused by the bacteria ''[[Salmonella]] pullorum'' and other bacterial diseases common in domestic poultry.\nThe chicks, and to a slightly lesser extent the adults, are incapable of using vegetable-based proteins and fats.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Their dietary requirements cannot be met with commercial processed food materials. As a result, they are exceedingly rare in captivity.\n\n==Habitat==\nIt is common in forests and scrub [[habitat (ecology)|habitats]], and is commonly spotted at sites such as [[Kitulgala]], [[Yala National Park|Yala]], and [[Sinharaja Forest Reserve|Sinharaja]].\n\n==Tailless mutant==\nIn 1868, the English [[naturalist]] [[Charles Darwin]] denied incorrectly the existence of a tailless [[mutant]] of Sri Lankan junglefowl, described in 1807 by the Dutch [[zoologist]] [[Coenraad Jacob Temminck]].<ref>Grouw, Hein van, Dekkers, Wim & Rookmaaker, Kees (2017). On Temminck's tailless Ceylon Junglefowl, and how Darwin denied their existence. ''Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club (London)'', 137 (4), 261-271. https://doi.org/10.25226/bboc.v137i4.2017.a3</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n[[File:Lithograph Tailless Ceylon Junglefowl (Jean-Gabriel Pr\u00eatre, 1806).jpg|thumb|left| [[Lithograph]] of tailless mutant of Sri Lankan junglefowl by [[Jean-Gabriel Pr\u00eatre]] (1805 or 1806) commissioned by [[Coenraad Jacob Temminck]] ([[Naturalis Biodiversity Center]], [[Leiden]], the [[Netherlands]])]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n==External links==\n*'''ARKive''' - [https://web.archive.org/web/20060721013218/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Gallus_lafayetii/ images and movies of the Sri Lanka junglefowl ''(Gallus lafayetii)'']\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q256168}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:junglefowl, Sri Lankan}}\n[[Category:Junglefowls|Sri Lankan junglefowl]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1831|Sri Lankan junglefowl]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Sri Lankan junglefowl\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{Cite iucn | author = BirdLife International | title = ''Gallus lafayettii'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22679209A92807515 | date = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22679209A92807515.en }}</ref>\n| image = Flickr - Rainbirder - Ceylon Junglefowl (Gallus lafayetii) Male.jpg\n| image_caption = Male in [[Sinharaja Forest Reserve]], Sri Lanka\n| genus = Gallus\n| species = lafayettii\n| authority = [[Ren\u00e9-Primev\u00e8re Lesson|Lesson]], 1831\n| range_map = Gallus lfeyetii map.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Range\n}}\n\nThe '''Sri Lankan junglefowl''' (''Gallus lafayettii''), also known as the '''Ceylon junglefowl''', is a member of the  [[Galliformes]] bird order which is [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] to [[Sri Lanka]], where it is the [[national bird]]. It is closely related to the [[red junglefowl]] (''G. gallus''), the wild [[junglefowl]] from which the chicken was domesticated. However, a whole-genome molecular study rather show that Sri Lankan junglefowl and [[grey junglefowl]] are genetically sister species than with the red junglefowl.<ref name=Lawal>{{ cite journal | last1=Lawal | first1=RA. | display-authors=etal  | year=2020 | title=The wild species genome ancestry of domestic chickens | journal=BMC Biology | volume=18 | issue=13 | pages=13 | doi=10.1186/s12915-020-0738-1 | doi-access=free | pmid=32050971 }}</ref> Sri Lankan junglefowl and red junglefowl diverged about 2.8 million years ago whereas, time of divergence between the Sri Lankan junglefowl and grey junglefowl was 1.8 million years ago.<ref name = Lawal /> \n\nEvidence of introgressive hybridization from Sri Lanka junglefowl has also been established in domestic chicken.<ref name = Lawal /> The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] of the Sri Lankan junglefowl commemorates the French aristocrat [[Gilbert du Motier, marquis de La Fayette]]. In [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]], it is known as {{lang|si|\u0dc0\u0dc5\u0dd2 \u0d9a\u0dd4\u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dc5\u0dcf}} ({{transl|si|wali kukula}})<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnhsenvis.nic.in/pdf/vol%203%20(1).pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-10-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401015111/http://www.bnhsenvis.nic.in/pdf/vol%203%20%281%29.pdf |archive-date=2010-04-01 |df= }}</ref> and in [[Tamil language|Tamil]], it is known as \u0b87\u0bb2\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bcb\u0bb4\u0bbf (''ila\u1e45kaik k\u0101\u1e6d\u1e6dukk\u014d\u1e3bi'').\n{{Cladogram\n|caption=[[Cladogram]] showing the species in the genus ''[[Gallus (genus)|Gallus]]''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Tiley | first1=G.P. | last2=Pandey | first2=A. | last3=Kimball | first3=R.T. | last4=Braun | first4=E.L. | last5=Burleigh | first5=J.G. | year=2020| title=Whole genome phylogeny of ''Gallus'': introgression and data\u2011type effects | journal=Avian Research | volume=11 | issue=7 | doi=10.1186/s40657-020-00194-w | doi-access=free }}</ref>\n|align=right\n|cladogram={{Cladex| style=font-size:80%;line-height:75%;width:320px;\n|label1=''Gallus''&nbsp; \n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=[[Grey junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus sonneratii''\n         |2=[[Sri Lankan junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus lafayettii''\n         }}\n      |2=[[Red junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus gallus''\n      }}\n    |2=[[Green junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus varius''\n    }}\n}}\n}}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Flickr - Rainbirder - Ceylon Junglefowl (Gallus lafayetii) female.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Female at [[Sinharaja Forest Reserve]], Sri Lanka]]\nAs with other junglefowl, the Sri Lankan junglefowl is strongly [[sexually dimorphic]]; the male is much larger than the female, with more vivid plumage and a highly exaggerated wattle and comb.\n\nThe male Sri Lankan junglefowl ranges from {{convert|66|\u2013|72|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length<ref>del Hoyo, J. Elliott, A. and Sargatal, J. [[Handbook of the Birds of the World]] [[Lynx Edicions]], [[Barcelona]]</ref> and {{convert|790|-|1140|g|lb|abbr=on}} in weight, essentially resembling a large, muscular [[rooster]].<ref name = \"CRC\">''CRC Handbook of Avian Body Masses'' by John B. Dunning Jr. (Editor). CRC Press (1992), {{ISBN|978-0-8493-4258-5}}.</ref> The male has orange-red body plumage, and dark purple to black wings and tail. The feathers of the mane descending from head to base of [[Vertebral column|spine]] are golden, and the face has bare red skin and wattles. The comb is red with a yellow centre.  As with the [[green junglefowl]], the cock does not possess an [[Plumage#Eclipse plumage|eclipse plumage]].\n\nThe female is much smaller, at only {{convert|35|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|510|-|645|g|lb|abbr=on}} in weight, with dull brown [[plumage]] with white patterning on the lower belly and breast, ideal [[camouflage]] for a nesting bird.<ref name= \"CRC\"/>\n\n==Classification==\nThis is one of four [[species]] of birds in the genus ''[[Gallus (biology)|Gallus]]''. The other three members of the genus are [[red junglefowl]] (''G. gallus''), [[grey junglefowl]] (''G. sonneratii''), and [[green junglefowl]] (''G. varius'').\n\nThe Sri Lankan junglefowl is most closely related to the grey junglefowl,<ref>International Chicken Polymorphism Map Consortium {{cite journal | last1 = Wong | first1 = GK| year = 2004 | title = A genetic variation map for chicken with 2.8 million single-nucleotide polymorphisms | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 432 | issue = | pages = 717\u2013722 | doi = 10.1038/nature03156 | pmid = 15592405 | pmc=2263125|display-authors=etal}}</ref> though physically the male resembles the red junglefowl. Female Sri Lanka junglefowl are very similar to those of the grey junglefowl. Like the green junglefowl, Sri Lankan junglefowl are island species that have evolved side by side with their similarly stranded island predators and competitors. Uniquely complex anti-predator behaviors and foraging strategies are integral components in the long evolutionary story of the Sri Lankan junglefowl.\n\n==Behaviour==\nAs with other jungle fowl, Sri Lankan jungle fowl are primarily terrestrial. They spend most of their time foraging for food by scratching the ground for various [[seed]]s, fallen [[fruit]], and [[insect]]s.\n\nFemales lay two to four [[Egg (biology)|egg]]s in a nest, either on the forest floor in steep hill country or in the abandoned nests of other birds and squirrels. Like the grey and green junglefowl, male Sri Lankan junglefowl play an active role in nest protection and chick rearing.\n\n==Reproduction==\n[[File:Gallus lafayettii MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.9.31.jpg|thumb| ''Gallus lafayettii'' - [[MHNT]]]]\n[[File:Gallus lafayetii.jpg|thumb]]\nThe reproductive strategy of this species is best described as facultative [[polyandry]], in that a single female is typically linked with two or three males that form a pride of sorts. These males are likely to be siblings. The female pairs with the alpha male of the pride and nests high off the ground.\n\nHer eggs are highly variable in colour, but generally are cream with a yellow or pink tint. Purple or brownish spots are common.\n\nOccasionally, a female produces red eggs or blotched eggs.\n\nThe hen incubates her eggs, while the alpha male guards her nest from a nearby perch during the nesting season. The beta males remain in close proximity, and guard the nesting territory from intruders or potential predators, such as rival males, or snakes and mongooses. Sri Lankan junglefowl are unique amongst the junglefowl in the brevity of their incubation, which may be as short as 20 days as contrasted with the 21\u201326 days of the green junglefowl.\n\nThe chicks require a constant diet of live food, usually insects and isopods such as [[sowbug]]s and [[pillbug]]s. In particular, the juveniles of [[land crab]]s are also highly important to the growth and survivability of the juvenile and subadult Sri Lankan junglefowl. In captivity, this species is particularly vulnerable to a poultry disease caused by the bacteria ''[[Salmonella]] pullorum'' and other bacterial diseases common in domestic poultry.\nThe chicks, and to a slightly lesser extent the adults, are incapable of using vegetable-based proteins and fats.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Their dietary requirements cannot be met with commercial processed food materials. As a result, they are exceedingly rare in captivity.\n\n==Habitat==\nIt is common in forests and scrub [[habitat (ecology)|habitats]], and is commonly spotted at sites such as [[Kitulgala]], [[Yala National Park|Yala]], and [[Sinharaja Forest Reserve|Sinharaja]].\n\n==Tailless mutant==\nIn 1868, the English [[naturalist]] [[Charles Darwin]] denied incorrectly the existence of a tailless [[mutant]] of Sri Lankan junglefowl, described in 1807 by the Dutch [[zoologist]] [[Coenraad Jacob Temminck]].<ref>Grouw, Hein van, Dekkers, Wim & Rookmaaker, Kees (2017). On Temminck's tailless Ceylon Junglefowl, and how Darwin denied their existence. ''Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club (London)'', 137 (4), 261-271. https://doi.org/10.25226/bboc.v137i4.2017.a3</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n[[File:Lithograph Tailless Ceylon Junglefowl (Jean-Gabriel Pr\u00eatre, 1806).jpg|thumb|left| [[Lithograph]] of tailless mutant of Sri Lankan junglefowl by [[Jean-Gabriel Pr\u00eatre]] (1805 or 1806) commissioned by [[Coenraad Jacob Temminck]] ([[Naturalis Biodiversity Center]], [[Leiden]], the [[Netherlands]])]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n==External links==\n*'''ARKive''' - [https://web.archive.org/web/20060721013218/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Gallus_lafayetii/ images and movies of the Sri Lanka junglefowl ''(Gallus lafayetii)'']\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q256168}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:junglefowl, Sri Lankan}}\n[[Category:Junglefowls|Sri Lankan junglefowl]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1831|Sri Lankan junglefowl]]\n", "name_user": "Akinyanju", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update the based on the recent findings of the species", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sri_Lankan_junglefowl"}
{"title_page": "Ode-Irele", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n'''Ikale Kingdom''' ('''Ikale''') is a tribe in [[Ondo State]] of [[Nigeria]], West Africa.<ref>{{GEOnet2|B170AFEED3D944DD8373142CCAEE3B93|Ikoya-Ikale (Approved - N) }}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> It is the administrative headquarters for the [[Ikoya-Ikale|Abodi in Council]]. Ikoya is located {{Convert|10|km|mi|0}} by road south of the town of [[Ikale]].\n\nAbodi of Ikale is the paramount ruler of Ikale Kingdom. He is a first class King by ranking among the traditional rulers of Yoruba land.\nOba Rebuja of Osoro\nOba Olofun of Irele\nOba Jegun of Idepe\nOba Halu/Lapoki of Ode-Aye\nOba Odogbo of Omi\nOba Orungberuwa of Ode-Erinj\nOba Larogbo of Akotogbo\nOba Lumure of Ayeka\nOba Olura of Igbinsin-oloto\nOba Ahaba of Ajagba\nOba Obagberume of Igbodigo\nOba Laragunshin of Iyansan\nOba Olu of Igodan-lisa\nOba Lighogbo of Ijo-osun\nOba orofun of Iju-Odo\nOba Majuwa of Moribodo-Ilutitun, \nOloja Odofin of iju-Oke,\nOlaja of Lafelepa\nOloja of Ayetedo\n <ref>{{Cite news|title=|newspaper=Nigeria News |url=http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/news/general/41432-Another-Ondo-monarch-deposed.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421193712/http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/news/general/41432-Another-Ondo-monarch-deposed.html |archivedate=21 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n|url=http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/news/409767-ondo-deaths-youths-committed-sacrilege-says-chief.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6XzA9wLCK |archivedate=22 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> This was followed by the deaths of twenty youths in the community due to [[Methanol#Toxicity|methanol poisoning]] from drinking a locally distilled brew containing unidentified herbs.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Disease Outbreak in Ondo State is Punishment from the 'gods'|date=21 April 2015 |newspaper=Nigeria News |url=http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/headline/410081-disease-outbreak-in-ondo-state-is-punishment-from-the-gods.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421194330/http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/headline/410081-disease-outbreak-in-ondo-state-is-punishment-from-the-gods.html |archivedate=21 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Winsor, Morgan |date=21 April 2015 |title=Nigeria's Mysterious Epidemic Linked To Contaminated Alcohol And Methanol Poisoning, Not Ebola |newspaper=International Business Times |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/nigerias-mysterious-epidemic-linked-contaminated-alcohol-methanol-poisoning-not-ebola-1890564 |archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/6XxiijlIR |archivedate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Chief Moses Enimade, the king of Ode-Irele, believes that the deaths were in punishment for the sacrilege.<ref name=\"Omojuwa\" /><ref name=\"NN1\" />\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Cite news|author=Omosule, Segun |date=7 July 2011 |title=Educational Development in Irele and its patrons|newspaper=Ikale Voice|url=http://ikalevoice.com/4/?p=940 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213125952/http://ikalevoice.com/4/?p=940 |archivedate=13 December 2013 |url-status=live}}\n{{-}}\n\n{{Coord|06|29|23|N|004|52|09|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Ondo State]]\n\n\n{{OndoNG-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n'''Ode-Irele''' ('''Irele''') is a town in [[Ondo State]] of [[Nigeria]], West Africa.<ref>{{GEOnet2|B170AFEED3D944DD8373142CCAEE3B93|Ode-Irele (Approved - N) }}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> It is the administrative headquarters for the [[Irele|Irele Local Government Area]]. Ode-Irele is located {{Convert|10|km|mi|0}} by road west of the town of [[Okitipupa]].\n\nThere is a king in Ode-Irele called the Olofun(HRM Olarewaju Lebi). He is the paramount ruler of Ode-Irele Kingdom. He is a first class King by ranking. He comes from the Oyenusi Ruling house.  There are  three ruling houses in Irele. These are the Orunbemekun, Jagboju and Oyenusi Ruling houses. <ref>{{Cite news|title=Another Ondo monarch deposed |date=28 June 2010 |newspaper=Nigeria News |url=http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/news/general/41432-Another-Ondo-monarch-deposed.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421193712/http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/news/general/41432-Another-Ondo-monarch-deposed.html |archivedate=21 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April 2015 a group of young men broke into the [[Sanctum sanctorum|inner sanctum]] of the shrine to Molokun, the god of the land, in Ode-Irele.<ref name=\"Omojuwa\">{{Cite news|title=Ondo mysterious disease is spiritual, local chief reveals mystery behind deaths |date=18 April 2015 |newspaper=Omojuwa |url=http://omojuwa.com/2015/04/ondo-mysterious-disease-is-spiritual-local-chief-reveals-mystery-behind-deaths/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Xz9kYIpl |archivedate=22 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Their objective was apparently to obtain certain items of spiritual power.<ref name=\"NN1\">{{Cite news|title=Ondo deaths: Youths committed sacrilege, says Chief |date=18 April 2015 |newspaper=Nigeria News |url=http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/news/409767-ondo-deaths-youths-committed-sacrilege-says-chief.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6XzA9wLCK |archivedate=22 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> This was followed by the deaths of twenty youths in the community due to [[Methanol#Toxicity|methanol poisoning]] from drinking a locally distilled brew containing unidentified herbs.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Disease Outbreak in Ondo State is Punishment from the 'gods'|date=21 April 2015 |newspaper=Nigeria News |url=http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/headline/410081-disease-outbreak-in-ondo-state-is-punishment-from-the-gods.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421194330/http://news2.onlinenigeria.com/headline/410081-disease-outbreak-in-ondo-state-is-punishment-from-the-gods.html |archivedate=21 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Winsor, Morgan |date=21 April 2015 |title=Nigeria's Mysterious Epidemic Linked To Contaminated Alcohol And Methanol Poisoning, Not Ebola |newspaper=International Business Times |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/nigerias-mysterious-epidemic-linked-contaminated-alcohol-methanol-poisoning-not-ebola-1890564 |archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/6XxiijlIR |archivedate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Chief Moses Enimade, the king of Ode-Irele, believes that the deaths were in punishment for the sacrilege.<ref name=\"Omojuwa\" /><ref name=\"NN1\" />\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Cite news|author=Omosule, Segun |date=7 July 2011 |title=Educational Development in Irele and its patrons|newspaper=Ikale Voice|url=http://ikalevoice.com/4/?p=940 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213125952/http://ikalevoice.com/4/?p=940 |archivedate=13 December 2013 |url-status=live}}\n{{-}}\n\n{{Coord|06|29|23|N|004|52|09|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Ondo State]]\n\n\n{{OndoNG-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "197.211.61.66", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ode-Irele"}
{"title_page": "5-MeO-2-TMT", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| verifiedrevid = 413277905\n| IUPAC_name = 2-(5-methoxy-2-methyl-H-indol-3-yl)-N,N-dimethylethanamine\n| image = 5-MeO-2,N,N-TMT.svg\n| width = 200\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| pregnancy_AU =  \n| pregnancy_US =  \n| pregnancy_category =  \n| legal_AU =  \n| legal_CA =  \n| legal_DE = NpSG\n| legal_UK = Class A\n| legal_US =  \n| legal_status =  \n| routes_of_administration =  \n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability =  \n| protein_bound =  \n| metabolism =  \n| elimination_half-life =  \n| excretion =  \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number = 67292-68-6\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = XZ2CCP18I2\n| ATC_prefix =  \n| ATC_suffix =  \n| PubChem = 49756\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 45143\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 7143\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=14 | H=20 | N=2 | O=1 \n| molecular_weight = 232.321 g/mol\n| smiles = CC1=C(C2=C(N1)C=CC(=C2)OC)CCN(C)C\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C14H20N2O/c1-10-12(7-8-16(2)3)13-9-11(17-4)5-6-14(13)15-10/h5-6,9,15H,7-8H2,1-4H3\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = ACEHBQPPDDGCGZ-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| melting_point =  \n| melting_high =  \n}}\n\n'''5-Methoxy-2,''N'',''N''-trimethyltryptamine''' ('''5-MeO-2,''N'',''N''-TMT''', '''5-MeO-TMT''') is a [[psychoactive drug]] of the [[tryptamine]] [[chemical class]] which acts as a [[psychedelic drug|psychedelic]]. It was first [[chemical synthesis|synthesized]] by [[Alexander Shulgin]] and reported in his book [[TiHKAL]] (\"Tryptamines i Have Known And Loved\").<ref>[http://www.erowid.org/library/books_online/tihkal/tihkal45.shtml Erowid Online Books : \"TIHKAL\" - #45 5-MEO-TMT]</ref> 5-MeO-TMT is claimed to show psychoactive effects at a dosage of 75-150&nbsp;mg orally, but these are relatively mild compared to those of other similar [[chemical compound|compound]]s. This suggests that while the [[methyl]] [[functional group|group]] on the 2-position of the [[molecule]] has impaired the [[binding (molecular)|binding]] of [[metabolic]] [[enzyme]]s like [[monoamine oxidase]] (MAO), it is also interfering with binding to and/or activation of the [[serotonin]] [[5-HT2A|5-HT<sub>2A</sub>]] [[Receptor (biochemistry)|receptor]], the target responsible for mediating the [[hallucinogen]]ic effects of such compounds.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2,N,N-TMT|2,''N'',''N''-Trimethyltryptamine]] (2,''N'',''N''-TMT)\n* [[5-Methoxy-7,N,N-trimethyltryptamine|5-MeO-7-TMT]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.erowid.org/library/books_online/tihkal/tihkal45.shtml 5-MeO-TMT Entry in ''TIHKAL'']\n* [http://tihkal.info/read.php?domain=tk&id=45 5-MeO-TMT Entry in TiHKAL \u2022 info]\n\n{{Tryptamines}}\n{{Hallucinogenic tryptamines}}\n{{TiHKAL}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5-Methoxy-2,N,N-Trimethyltryptamine}}\n[[Category:Psychedelic tryptamines]]\n[[Category:Designer drugs]]\n\n\n{{hallucinogen-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| verifiedrevid = 413277905\n| IUPAC_name = 2-(5-methoxy-2-methyl-H-indol-3-yl)-N,N-dimethylethanamine\n| image = 5-MeO-2,N,N-TMT.svg\n| width = 200\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| pregnancy_AU =  \n| pregnancy_US =  \n| pregnancy_category =  \n| legal_AU =  \n| legal_CA =  \n| legal_DE = NpSG\n| legal_UK = Class A\n| legal_US =  \n| legal_status =  \n| routes_of_administration =  \n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability =  \n| protein_bound =  \n| metabolism =  \n| elimination_half-life =  \n| excretion =  \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number = 67292-68-6\n| ATC_prefix =  \n| ATC_suffix =  \n| PubChem = 49756\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 45143\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 7143\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=14 | H=20 | N=2 | O=1 \n| molecular_weight = 232.321 g/mol\n| smiles = CC1=C(C2=C(N1)C=CC(=C2)OC)CCN(C)C\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C14H20N2O/c1-10-12(7-8-16(2)3)13-9-11(17-4)5-6-14(13)15-10/h5-6,9,15H,7-8H2,1-4H3\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = ACEHBQPPDDGCGZ-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| melting_point =  \n| melting_high =  \n}}\n\n'''5-Methoxy-2,''N'',''N''-trimethyltryptamine''' ('''5-MeO-2,''N'',''N''-TMT''', '''5-MeO-TMT''') is a [[psychoactive drug]] of the [[tryptamine]] [[chemical class]] which acts as a [[psychedelic drug|psychedelic]]. It was first [[chemical synthesis|synthesized]] by [[Alexander Shulgin]] and reported in his book [[TiHKAL]] (\"Tryptamines i Have Known And Loved\").<ref>[http://www.erowid.org/library/books_online/tihkal/tihkal45.shtml Erowid Online Books : \"TIHKAL\" - #45 5-MEO-TMT]</ref> 5-MeO-TMT is claimed to show psychoactive effects at a dosage of 75-150&nbsp;mg orally, but these are relatively mild compared to those of other similar [[chemical compound|compound]]s. This suggests that while the [[methyl]] [[functional group|group]] on the 2-position of the [[molecule]] has impaired the [[binding (molecular)|binding]] of [[metabolic]] [[enzyme]]s like [[monoamine oxidase]] (MAO), it is also interfering with binding to and/or activation of the [[serotonin]] [[5-HT2A|5-HT<sub>2A</sub>]] [[Receptor (biochemistry)|receptor]], the target responsible for mediating the [[hallucinogen]]ic effects of such compounds.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2,N,N-TMT|2,''N'',''N''-Trimethyltryptamine]] (2,''N'',''N''-TMT)\n* [[5-Methoxy-7,N,N-trimethyltryptamine|5-MeO-7-TMT]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.erowid.org/library/books_online/tihkal/tihkal45.shtml 5-MeO-TMT Entry in ''TIHKAL'']\n* [http://tihkal.info/read.php?domain=tk&id=45 5-MeO-TMT Entry in TiHKAL \u2022 info]\n\n{{Tryptamines}}\n{{Hallucinogenic tryptamines}}\n{{TiHKAL}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5-Methoxy-2,N,N-Trimethyltryptamine}}\n[[Category:Psychedelic tryptamines]]\n[[Category:Designer drugs]]\n\n\n{{hallucinogen-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/5-MeO-2-TMT"}
