orea-doesnt-stop-you-from-being-homophobic/ |website=Quartz |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>}}\n| headquarters     = 7, Gukhoe-daero 68-gil, [[Yeongdeungpo District]], [[Seoul]]\n| international    = \n| national         = [[Together Citizens' Party]] (Party-list faction)\n| website          = {{URL|theminjoo.kr/}}\n| country          = South Korea\n| leader1_title    = [[President of South Korea]]\n| leader1_name     = [[Moon Jae-in]]\n| leader2_title    = Leader\n| leader2_name     = [[Lee Hae-chan]]\n| leader3_title    = Floor leader\n| leader3_name     = [[Lee In-young]]\n| leader4_title    = Secretary-General\n| leader4_name     = [[Yun Ho-jung]]\n| leader5_title    = Chair of the Policy Planning Committee\n| leader5_name     = Cho Jeong-sik\n| native_name      = {{nobold|\ub354\ubd88\uc5b4\ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9}}<br />''Deobureominjudang''\n| native_name_lang = ko\n| predecessor      = [[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2011)|Democratic Party]]<br>New Politics Alliance\n| merger           = [[Minjoo Party (2014)|Minjoo Party]]\n| merged           = \n| newspaper        = \n| youth_wing       = \n| membership_year  = 2018\n| membership       = 3,579,111\n| position         = {{Nowrap|[[Centrism|Centre]]<ref name=\"centrist\">The Democratic Party of Korea is described as a centrist party by numerous sources:{{bulleted list\n|{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Democratic-Party-of-Korea|title=Democratic Party of Korea|quote=Democratic Party of Korea (DP), Korean Daeburo Minjudang, '''centrist-liberal political party''' in South Korea.|work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|Britannica]]}}\n|{{cite web|author=Andrew Walter|url=https://www.rsis.edu.sg/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/CO19219.pdf|title=Political Populism: Eroding Asia\u2019s Complex Interdependence?|quote=The South Korean President Moon Jae-in\u2019s centrist-liberal Democratic Party has also reflected and tactically deployed the considerable popular nationalist sentiment in South Korean society as he vowed in early August that in the escalating bilateral trade dispute the country would \u201cnever again lose to Japan\u201d.|work=[[Nanyang Technological University]]|publisher=[[S. Rajaratnam School of International Studies]]|date=31 October 2019}}\n|{{cite web|url=https://en.portal.santandertrade.com/analyse-markets/south-korea/economic-political-outline|title=South Korea: Economic and Political Outline|quote=The Minjoo Party: centre, socially liberal main opposition party, result of a 2014 merger between the Democratic Party and the New Political Vision Party, first party in the Parliament since August 2017|date=July 2019|accessdate=21 July 2019|publisher=Santander}}\n|{{cite web|url=https://europeelects.eu/2019/11/14/the-justice-party-and-the-south-korean-left-a-movement-with-potential-but-divided-and-struggling/|title=The Justice Party and the South Korean Left: A movement with potential, but divided and struggling|quote=With most of national politics dominated by the centrist Democratic Party and the right-wing Liberty Korea Party ({{lang|ko-Hang|\uc790\uc720\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9}}), successor to the former governing Saenuri Party, there is little space for the Justice Party to find an opening for electoral success.|work=[[Europe Elects]]|date=14 November 2019}}\n|{{cite web|first=JH|last=Ahn|title=South Korea split over whether to aid \"arch-nemesis\" in flood relief|url=https://www.nknews.org/2016/09/south-korea-split-over-whether-to-aid-arch-nemesis-in-flood-relief/|quote=Her party, Saenuri, has also remained silent on the issue, in sharp contrast to centrist Minjoo Party [''sic''], which on Monday urged Seoul to look beyond politics and help its neighbor.|work=NK news.org|date=19 September 2016}}\n}}</ref> to [[centre-left]]<ref name=\"CL\">{{bulleted list\n|{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39855956|title=Moon Jae-in: South Korean liberal claims presidency|quote=Mr Moon, of the centre-left Democratic Party, unsuccessfully ran against Ms Park in 2012 elections.|date=9 May 2017|accessdate=2 October 2019|publisher=BBC}}\n|{{cite web|url=https://www.foreignbrief.com/daily-news/south-koreans-set-to-continue-backing-president-moons-agenda-in-local-elections/|title=South Koreans set to continue backing President Moon\u2019s agenda in local elections|quote=his centre-left Democratic Party of Korea is expected to make major political gains|date=13 June 2017|accessdate=7 December 2019|publisher=Foreign Brief}}\n}}</ref>}}\n| colours      = [[Blue]]<ref group=\"N\">Officially described as \"sea blue\" ({{lang|ko|\ubc14\ub2e4\ud30c\ub791}}) by the party.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=421&aid=0000732800 |script-title=ko:\ubc14\ub2e4\ud30c\ub791 '\uc0c8\uc815\uce58\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc5f0\ud569', \uc369\uc9c0 \uc54a\ub294 \ubc14\ub2e4\ucc98\ub7fc |trans-title=|last=Park |first=Cheoljoong |date=2014-03-16 |language=Korean |publisher=News1 |accessdate=2014-04-22}}</ref>\n| seats1_title = Seats in the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n| seats1       = {{Composition bar|163|300|{{Minjoo Party of Korea/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = Metropolitan mayor and Gubernatorial\n| seats2       = {{Composition bar|14|17|hex={{Minjoo Party of Korea/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = Municipal Mayors\n| seats3       = {{Composition bar|151|226|{{Minjoo Party of Korea/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = Seats within local government\n| seats4       = {{Composition bar|2290|3750|{{Minjoo Party of Korea/meta/color}}}}\n| think_tank   = [[The Institute for Democracy]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\ub354\ubd88\uc5b4\ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9\n|hanja=\ub354\ubd88\uc5b4\u6c11\u4e3b\u9ee8<ref group=\"N\" name=\"hanja-deo\">{{lang|zh-Hant|{{uline|\u5171\u540c}}\u6c11\u4e3b\u9ee8}} or other variants are translated names in [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[Japanese language|Japanese]].</ref>\n|rr=Deobureominjudang\n|mr=T\u014fbur\u014fminjudang\n|othername1=The Minjoo\n|hangul1=\ub354\ubbfc\uc8fc\n|hanja1={{lang|ko-Hant|\ub354\u6c11\u4e3b}}\n|rr1=Deominju\n|mr1=T\u014fminju\n|othername2=Democratic Party\n|hangul2=\ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9\n|hanja2={{linktext|lang=ko-Hant|\u6c11\u4e3b\u9ee8}}\n|rr2=Minjudang\n|mr2=Minjudang\n}}\n[[File:Deomin Jungangdang at Seoul in 2018.jpg|thumb|200px|Headquarters of the Democratic Party]]\nThe '''Democratic Party'''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news1.kr/articles/?2805887 |script-title=ko: \ub354\ubbfc\uc8fc, \uc624\ub298 \uc6d0\uc678 \ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9 \ud1b5\ud569...'\ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9' \uc774\ub984 \ub418\ucc3e\ub294\ub2e4 |trans-title=|last= Park |first= Seung-ju |date=2016-10-19 |language=Korean |publisher=News1 |accessdate=2016-10-19}}\".</ref> ({{Korean|hangul=\ub354\ubd88\uc5b4\ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9|hanja={{lang|ko-Hant|\ub354\ubd88\uc5b4\u6c11\u4e3b\u9ee8}} |rr=Deobureominjudang|mr=|lit=''Together Democratic Party''}}; short form {{lang|ko-Hang|\ubbfc\uc8fc, \ub354\ubbfc\uc8fc}} \"Minjoo\", \"Deominjoo\", now known as \"Minjudang\" \ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9 in South Korean media since 2016).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tbs.seoul.kr/news/bunya.do?&typ_800=N&seq_800=10127679|title=Main Opposition To Be Called 'The Minjoo Party Of Korea' |trans-title=|last= |first= |date=2015-12-30 |publisher=[[Traffic Broadcasting System]]|work=tbs.seoul.kr |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref> formerly the '''New Politics Alliance for Democracy''' (NPAD),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://khnews.kheraldm.com/view.php?ud=20140320001513&md=20140323004048_BL&kr=1 |script-title=ko:\uc0c8\uc815\uce58\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc5f0\ud569 \uc601\ubb38 \ub2f9\uba85 \ud655\uc815 |trans-title=|last=Choi |first=He-suk |date=2014-03-20 |language=Korean |publisher=The Korea Herald |accessdate=2014-04-22}}</ref> is a [[Centrism|centrist]],<ref name=\"centrist\"/> [[Liberalism in South Korea|liberal]]<ref name=\"liberal\"/> political party in [[South Korea]].\n\nThe party was founded on 26 March 2014 as a merger of the [[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2011)|Democratic Party]] and the preparatory committee of the New Political Vision Party (NPVP). The former Democratic Party was legally absorbed into the NPAD after the latter's creation, while the preparatory committee of the NPVP was dissolved, with members who supported the merger joining the NPAD individually.\n\n==History==\n===Formation and Ahn\u2013Kim chairmanship (March \u2013 July 2014)===\nThe Democratic Party was formed as the New Politics Alliance for Democracy ({{Korean|hangul=\uc0c8\uc815\uce58\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc5f0\ud569|rr=Saejeongchi Minju Yeonhap|labels=no }}) on 26 March 2014 after the independent faction led by [[Ahn Cheol-soo]], then in the process of forming a party called the New Political Vision Party, merged with the main opposition [[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2011)|Democratic Party]], led by [[Kim Han-gil]]. Ahn and Kim became joint leaders of the new party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.donga.com/List/3/all/26/407931/1|title=Democratic Party, Ahn Cheol-soo agree to create new party|newspaper=[[The Dong-A Ilbo]]|date=3 March 2014|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> The party performed poorly in [[2014 South Korean by-elections|by-elections that July]], however, and both leaders stepped down, having served for three months. Leadership of the party was assumed by an emergency committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2992867|title=Co-chairmen quit amid election rubble|newspaper=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=1 August 2014|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Ahn\u2013Moon controversy and split (2015\u201316)===\nThe next year, at a party convention on 7 February, [[Moon Jae-in]] was elected the new chairman of the party.<ref name=\"YonhapMoon\">{{cite news |url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2015/02/08/73/0301000000AEN20150208002152315F.html|title=Main opposition party picks ex-Roh aide as new leader}}</ref> Moon, who had previously served as chief of staff for former president [[Roh Moo-hyun]],<ref name=\"YonhapMoon\" /> was the leader of the party's \"pro-Roh\" faction, which was opposed to Ahn and Kim. Moon came under fire for imposing a \"pro-Roh hegemony\" in the party, as Ahn and Kim were jeered and harassed at a memorial service for Roh held in May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2015/05/116_179489.html|title=Roh son's speech creates stir|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=24 May 2015|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe party hemorrhaged support as the factional conflict intensified, falling from around 40 to 30 percent in opinion polls.<ref name=\"HankyorehHonam\">{{cite news |url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/739721.html|title=In liberal stronghold, voters give main opposition party a lashing|newspaper=[[The Hankyoreh]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> A survey conducted on 12\u201314 November showed that supporters of the party wanted Ahn and Seoul mayor [[Park Won-soon]] to assume the leadership alongside Moon.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3011673|title=NPAD supporters wish for troika|newspaper=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=18 November 2015|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> On 29 November, Ahn rejected a proposal from Moon to establish a joint leadership,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20151129000428|title=Ahn rejects Moon's call for joint NPAD leadership|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=29 November 2015|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> and the next month he presented Moon with an ultimatum, demanding that he call a convention to elect a new party leader. Moon rejected the demand,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3012565|title=NPAD\u2019s Moon rejects Ahn demand|newspaper=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=9 December 2015|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> and Ahn left the party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2015/12/116_193056.html |title=Ahn Cheol-soo calls it quits with NPAD |newspaper=[[The Korea Times]] |date=13 December 2015 |accessdate=15 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425154538/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2015/12/116_193056.html |archivedate=25 April 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAhn was followed by a number of supportive NPAD assembly members, including his former co-leader Kim Han-gil,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3013479|title=Kim departs party he co-founded|newspaper=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=4 January 2016|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> and the group began preparations to form a new party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160104001029|title=Ahn vows to move forward as 3rd political force|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=4 January 2016|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> On 12 January, [[Kwon Rho-kap]], a former aide of President [[Kim Dae-jung]] and a popular figure in the party's traditional stronghold of [[Honam]], also exited the party, similarly citing Moon's \"pro-Roh hegemony\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160112000933|title=Former Kim DJ aide exits Minjoo Party|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=12 January 2016|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, Ahn and Kim merged their group with that of another defector from the NPAD, [[Chun Jung-bae]], to form the [[People's Party (South Korea, 2016)|People's Party]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tbsefm.seoul.kr/eNews/news.do?method=efmNewsInfo&idx_800=2143018&typ_800=N|title=Ahn Cheol-Soo, Chun Jung-Bae To Create New Party|publisher=TBS eFM|date=25 January 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the defections, the NPAD was renamed the Minjoo Party of Korea, and Moon resigned on 27 January 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/728307.html|title=Moon Jae-in steps down as leader of The Minjoo Party of Korea|newspaper=[[The Hankyoreh]]|date=28 January 2016|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Moon handed power to [[Kim Chong-in]], an academic and former assemblyman who had more recently served as economic advisor to conservative President [[Park Geun-hye]].<ref name=\"joongangidentity\">{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3016623|title=Minjoo\u2019s identity must be changed: Kim Chong-in|newspaper=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ap-south-koreans-go-to-the-polls-in-parliamentary-election-2016-4?IR=T|title=South Koreans go to the polls in parliamentary election|newspaper=[[Business Insider]]|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Kim was seen as an unexpected choice, as he had previously worked for the right-wing [[Chun Doo-hwan]] and [[Roh Tae-woo]] administrations in the 1980s,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/03/can-a-right-wing-defector-save-koreas-liberal-opposition/|title=Can a Right Wing Defector Save Korea's Liberal Opposition?|newspaper=[[The Diplomat]]|date=22 March 2016|accessdate=18 April 2016}}</ref> serving as an assembly member for the ruling [[Democratic Justice Party]] and as health and welfare minister under Roh.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1989/07/19/South-Korean-president-replaces-minister-6-Cabinet-members/5185616824000/|title=South Korean president replaces minister, 6 Cabinet members|publisher=[[United Press International]]|date=19 July 1989|accessdate=18 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Under Kim Chong-in (January \u2013 August 2016)===\nKim Chong-in viewed the pro\u2013Roh Moo-hyun faction and what he considered the extremist wing of the party as responsible for the party's troubles, and pledged to diminish their influence.<ref name=\"koreaheraldlee\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160315001042|title=Former P.M. quits Minjoo Party in nomination feud |newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=15 March 2016|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> In the lead-up to the [[2016 South Korean legislative election|2016 parliamentary election]] he moved against key members of the pro-Roh faction in the nominations process, deselecting [[Lee Hae-chan]], who had been Prime Minister under Roh and was now chairman of the Roh Moo-hyun Foundation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.khan.co.kr/khan_art_view.html?code=710100&artid=201603151815547|title=Kim Jong-in Gets Rid of Pro-Roh Dominance and Replaces the Mainstream: Signs of Factional Conflict|newspaper=[[The Kyunghyang Shinmun]]|date=15 April 2016|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Lee left the party in response.<ref name=\"koreaheraldlee\" /> Kim's moves proved controversial, and many of his nominations for the party's proportional representation list were rejected by the rest of the party leadership, while favored candidates of Moon were ranked near the top of the approved list. Kim offered to resign in March, but decided to stay on as leader after a personal visit from Moon.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160323000877 |title=Opposition chief quells dissenters|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=23 March 2016|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> Kim affirmed that he would continue to attempt to change the party's image, stating that the events had shown the party was \"still unable to move on from its old ways\".<ref name=\"joongangidentity\" />\n\nThough losing votes to the People's Party formed by Ahn, Chun and Kim Han-gil\u2014particularly in Honam<ref name=\"HankyorehHonam\" />\u2014the party emerged as the overall winner of the election, garnering a plurality of seats (120 seats) in the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]] with a margin of one seat over the [[Saenuri Party (2017)|Saenuri Party]]. [[Lee Hae-chan]] returned to the Assembly as an independent representing [[Sejong City]]. Following its election victory, Kim Chong-in announced that the Minjoo Party would change its emphasis from welfare to economic growth and structural reform. Kim stated that the party would also change its position to support the establishment of for-profit hospitals, in contrast to the party's earlier opposition to the policy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_203137.html |title=Opposition party shifting to growth |newspaper=[[The Korea Times]] |date=21 April 2016 |accessdate=21 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422193441/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_203137.html |archivedate=22 April 2016 |df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n===2017 presidential election victory===\nAfter the constitutional court impeached president [[Park Geun-hye]] over bribery, the Democratic Party's Moon Jae-in won the presidential election with a 41.1% plurality of the votes, with [[Hong Joon-pyo]] of Liberty Korea coming second with 24%.\n\n===Under Lee Hae-chan (August 2018~)===\nAfter 2017 presidential election victory, the party focused on next election, the Local elections. Democratic Party won again the election in 2018.\n\n===2018 Local election victory===\n{{See also|2018 South Korean local elections}}\n\n===2020 Legislative election victory===\n{{see also|2020 South Korean legislative election}}\n\n==Policies==\n{{Third-party|section|date=January 2020}}\nThe Party has a wide range of policies; some of these include:<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uac15\ub839\u00b7\ub2f9\ud5cc\u00b7\ub2f9\uaddc\u00b7\uc724\ub9ac\uaddc\ubc94 |url=https://theminjoo.kr/introduce/rule |publisher=Democratic Party of Korea |language=ko-kr |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic policies ===\n* Support a [[market economy]].\n* Encourage the growth of agricultural, livestock and fishing industries and develop agricultural and fishing villages.\n* Promote innovation and prepare South Korea for the jobs of the future.\n* Establish a department in charge of science and technology policy.\n* Raise the minimum wage.\n* Implement a version of the [[Green New Deal]] to move South Korea to [[carbon neutrality]] by 2050.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farand |first1=Chlo\u00e9 |title=South Korea to implement Green New Deal after ruling party election win |url=https://www.climatechangenews.com/2020/04/16/south-korea-implement-green-new-deal-ruling-party-election-win/ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |work=Climate Change News |publisher=Climate Home News Ltd |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Social policies ===\n* Strengthen the social safety net.\n* Guarantee healthcare and housing as a basic right.\n* Improve equal opportunity for all regardless of background, including in education.\n* Expand educational support for those in marginalized classes.\n* Support gender equality and oppose discrimination.\n\n===Foreign policies ===\n* Raise the morale of the military and strengthen rewards for veterans.\n* Strengthen the [[South Korea-United States relations|R.O.Korea\u2013U.S. alliance]] and follow proactive, cooperative diplomacy with neighbouring countries.\n* Expand support for enhancing the rights of Korean expatriates overseas.\n\n===Reunification of North and South Korea ===\n* Strongly support denuclearization on the [[Korean Peninsula]] and work toward peace.\n* Create a foundation for [[Korean reunification|reunification]] through exchange and cooperation.\n* Expand support for [[Human rights in North Korea|human rights]] and people\u2019s welfare.\n\n===Political reform ===\n* Recover people's trust in the government after the [[2016 South Korean political scandal]].\n* Fight corruption.\n* Give more money to local governments.\n* Integrate representative democracy and direct democracy.\n\n==List of leaders==\n===Chairpersons===\n*Note: {{sup|ERC}} - as head of Emergency Response Committee\n{|